":"about 1244","about 1245":"about 1245","about 1264":"about 1264","about 1265":"about 1265","after 1279":"after 1279","of Hazlewood, Yorkshire, England":"Hazlewood by Tadcaster, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","of Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","of Denton, Yorkshire,  England":"Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Denton, Yorkshire, England":"Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Weekley, Northamptonshire, England":"Weekley, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vavasour","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: status name for a feudal tenant ranking immediately below a baron, Old French  <i>vavas(s)our</i>,  <i>vavasseur</i>, Latin  <i>vassus vassorum</i> ‘vassal of vassals’."],"variants":[{"name":"Vavasseur","meanings":["English:  see  Vavasour  ."]},{"name":"Bavister","meanings":["English:   Titford   suggests that this is a late variant of   Vavasour  . It would be a dissimilated form of  <i>Vavister</i> and  <i>Vavester</i>, variants of  <i>Vavasour</i> that are evidenced in Lincs, also in Cambs, whence the name spread into Beds. Compare Willa Vavister, 1579 in   IGI   (Scopwick, Lincs); Thomas Vavister, 1615 in   IGI   (Cranwell, Lincs); Mary Vavester, 1708, Joseph Vavisor, 1738 in   IGI   (New Sleaford, Lincs)."]},{"name":"Vawser","meanings":["English: reduced form of   Vavasour  ."]}]},{"name":"Mauger","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Channel Islands (Guernsey and Jersey): from the Old French (Norman) personal name <i>Maug(i)er</i>, <i>Malg(i)er</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Madalgar(i)</i>, <i>Malger</i>, composed of the elements <i>madal</i> ‘council, meeting’ and <i>gar(i)</i> ‘spear’, or from <i>Amalgar(i)</i>, with the first element <i>amal</i> ‘capable, brave, eager’. C